<http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/ExecutionFlow/673>
        a                            capec:AttackStep ;
        capec:attackStep             "3" ;
        capec:attackStepDescription  "[Craft overflow content] The adversary crafts the content to be injected. If the intent is to simply cause the software to crash, the content need only consist of an excessive quantity of random data. If the intent is to leverage the overflow for execution of arbitrary code, the adversary will craft a set of content that not only overflows the targeted buffer but does so in such a way that the overwritten return address is replaced with one of the adversaries' choosing which points to code injected by the adversary." ;
        capec:attackStepPhase        "Experiment" ;
        capec:attackStepTechnique    "The formatting characters %s and %d are useful for observing memory and trying to print memory addresses. If an adversary has access to the log being written to they can observer this output and use it to help craft their attack." , "The formatting character %n is useful for adding extra data onto the buffer." .

