<http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/ExecutionFlow/1273>
        a                            capec:AttackStep ;
        capec:attackStep             "3" ;
        capec:attackStepDescription  "[Read directories or files which are not intended for public viewing.] The adversary attempts to access the discovered directories that allow access and may attempt to bypass server or application level ACLs by using manual or automated methods" ;
        capec:attackStepPhase        "Exploit" ;
        capec:attackStepTechnique    "Sequentially request a list of common base files to each directory discovered." , "Try other known exploits to elevate privileges sufficient to bypass protected directories." , "Access the files via direct URL and capture contents." , "Try multiple exploit techniques to list directory contents for directories that will not reveal their contents with a \"/\" request" , "List the files in the directory by issuing a request with the URL ending in a \"/\" slash." , "Attempt to bypass ACLs on directories by using methods that are known to work against some server types by appending data to the directory request. For instance, appending a Null byte to the end of the request which may cause an ACL to fail and allow access." .

capec-res:CAPEC-468  a                 capec:CAPEC ;
        dct:description                "An attacker makes use of Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) injection to steal data cross domain from the victim's browser. The attack works by abusing the standards relating to loading of CSS: 1. Send cookies on any load of CSS (including cross-domain) 2. When parsing returned CSS ignore all data that does not make sense before a valid CSS descriptor is found by the CSS parser." ;
        dct:identifier                 "468" ;
        dct:title                      "Generic Cross-Browser Cross-Domain Theft" ;
        capec:abstraction              "Standard" ;
        capec:hasModificationHistory   <http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/modificationHistory/46820201217> , <http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/modificationHistory/46820151109> , <http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/modificationHistory/46820220222> , <http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/modificationHistory/46820151207> ;
        capec:hasReference             <http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/reference/REF-405> ;
        capec:hasRelatedAttackPattern  <http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/relatedAttackPattern/468ChildOf242> ;
        capec:hasRelatedWeakness       cwe-res:CWE-177 , cwe-res:CWE-149 , cwe-res:CWE-838 , cwe-res:CWE-707 ;
        capec:hasSubmissionHistory     <http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/submissionHistory/46820140623> ;
        capec:mitigation               "Design: Prior to performing CSS parsing, require the CSS to start with well-formed CSS when it is a cross-domain load and the MIME type is broken. This is a browser level fix." , "Implementation: Perform proper HTML encoding and URL escaping" ;
        capec:prerequisite             "No new lines can be present in the injected CSS stringProper HTML or URL escaping of the \" and ' characters is not presentThe attacker has control of two injection points: pre-string and post-string" ;
        capec:resourceRequired         "Attacker controlled site/page to render a page referencing the injected CSS string" ;
        capec:status                   "Draft" ;
        capec:typicalSeverity          "Medium" .

<http://w3id.org/sepses/resource/capec/ExecutionFlow/6761>
        a                            capec:AttackStep ;
        capec:attackStep             "1" ;
        capec:attackStepDescription  "[Survey target application] Due to the number of NoSQL databases available and the numerous language/API combinations of each, the adversary must first survey the target application to learn what technologies are being leveraged and how they interact with user-driven data." ;
        capec:attackStepPhase        "Explore" ;
        capec:attackStepTechnique    "Determine the technology stack leveraged by the target application, such as the application server, drivers, frameworks, APIs, and databases being utilized." , "Identify areas of the application that interact with user input and may be involved with NoSQL queries." .

